definition.value: Eight copies of a chromosome in a cell or organism.
Nine copies of a chromosome in a cell or organism.
Ten copies of a chromosome in a cell or organism.

A trisomy quality inhering in a bearer when part of the bearer's extra chromosome is attached to one of the other chromosomes, or if one of the bearer's chromosomes has two copies of part of its chromosome.
Trisomies observed in humans.
Tetrasomies observed in humans.
Monosomies observed in humans.

The presence in a cell of two paired chromosomes from the same parent, with no chromosome of that pair from the other parent. This chromosome composition stems from non-disjunction events during meiosis. The disomy may be composed of both homologous chromosomes from one parent (heterodisomy) or a duplicate of one chromosome (isodisomy).
Uniparental disomy with duplication of a single chromosome from one parent.
Uniparental disomy with both homologous chromosomes from one parent.
A chromosomal copy number variation consisting of the absence of one of the copies of chromosome 1.
A chromosomal copy number variation consisting of the absence of one of the copies of chromosome 4.
A chromosomal copy number variation consisting of the absence of one of the copies of chromosome 5.
A chromosomal copy number variation consisting of the absence of one of the copies of chromosome 7.
A chromosomal copy number variation consisting of the absence of one of the copies of chromosome 11.
A chromosomal copy number variation consisting of the absence of one of the copies of chromosome 15.
A chromosomal copy number variation consisting of the absence of one of the copies of chromosome 17.
A chromosomal copy number variation consisting of the absence of one of the copies of chromosome 22.
A chromosomal copy number variation consisting of the absence of one of the copies of the X chromosome (making the person's karyotype 45,X).
Pentasomies observed in humans.
A pentasomy characterized by the presence of three extra X chromosomes (49,XXXXX).
The possession of four copies of chromosome 7 in an otherwise diploid cell.
The possession of four copies of chromosome 12 in an otherwise diploid cell.
The possession of four copies of chromosome 17 in an otherwise diploid cell.
The possession of four copies of the X chromosome in an otherwise diploid cell, making the person's karyotype 48,XXXX.
A chromosomal copy number variation consisting of the presence of a third copy of chromosome 8 in somatic cells.
A chromosomal copy number variation consisting of the presence of a third copy of chromosome 9 in somatic cells.
A chromosomal copy number variation consisting of the presence of a third copy of chromosome 13 in somatic cells.
A chromosomal copy number variation consisting of the presence of a third copy of chromosome 16 in somatic cells.
A chromosomal copy number variation consisting of the presence of a third copy of chromosome 18 in somatic cells.
A chromosomal copy number variation consisting of the presence of a third copy of chromosome 21 in somatic cells.
A chromosomal copy number variation consisting of the presence of a third copy of chromosome 22 in somatic cells.
A chromosomal copy number variation consisting of the presence of a third copy of the X chromosome in somatic cells, making the person's karyotype 47,XXX.

A chromosome disorder associated with trisomy of all or part of chromosome 18. Clinical manifestations include intrauterine growth retardation; cleft palate; congenital heart defects; microcephaly; micrognathia and clenched fists with overlapping fingers. Most affected fetuses do not survive to birth. Those who survive through their first year often have severe intellectual disability.

A chromosome syndrome associated with trisomy of all or part of chromosome 13. Clinical manifestations include congenital heart defects (e.g., patent ductus arteriosus), facial malformations (e.g., cleft lip; cleft palate; coloboma; microphthalmia); hypotonia, digit malformations (e.g., polydactyly or syndactyly), and seizures and severe intellectual disability associated with nervous system malformations.
A bodily disposition is a disposition that inheres in some extended organism.
A mental disposition is a bodily disposition that is realized in a mental process.

A personality is a complex sum of dispositions and predispositions towards mental processes and behaviour. It inheres in a person. Personality is not the same as mood, although a person may have a personality that includes a predisposition to moods of certain types, moods may come and go but a personality stays relatively constant, not appearing and disappearing. Personality typically changes slowly over time.
A personality trait manifesting itself in individual behavioral characteristics that are perceived as positive, assertive, social, and outgoing.
A state in which attention is largely directed outward from the self.
A state in which attention is largely directed inward upon one's self.
A process whereby individuals of a given gender are encouraged or otherwise helped in overcoming systematic bareers to gender equality (such as health or education disparities).
Women's empowerment is the process in which women elaborate and recreate what it is that they can be, do, and accomplish in a circumstance that they previously were denied.

Broadly, the strong social reactions of outrage, anger, or surprise, when accusations or rumours circulate or appear for some reason, regarding a person or persons who are perceived to have transgressed in some way.
A scandal involving allegations or information about possibly immoral or illegal sexual activities being made public.
A sex scandal of a political nature or involving political figures.
An action or event regarded as morally or legally wrong and causing general public outrage.
A war between organized groups within the same state or country.
The active, professed refusal of a citizen to obey certain laws, demands, orders or commands of a government.
Menstruation as experienced by transgender men.
Menstruation as experienced by cisgender women.
